entres on José Ingenieros, a Buenos Aires neighbourhood founded in a massive squatter invasion in the early 1970s, and describes how the military government's actions largely subdued a politically engaged community. DuBois traces how state repression and community militancy are remembered in José Ingenieros and how the tangled and ambiguous legacies of the past continued to shape ordinary people's lives years after the collapse of the military regime. This rich and evocative study breaks new ground in its exploration of the complex relationships between identity, memory, class formation, neoliberalism, and state violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuthoritarianismzArgentinazJosé Ingenieros IIxHistoryy20th century. 0aAuthoritarianismzArgentinazJosé Ingenieros IIxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil-military relationszArgentinazJosé Ingenieros IIxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil-military relationszArgentinazJosé Ingenieros IIxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor movementzArgentinazJosé Ingenieros IIxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor movementzArgentinazJosé Ingenieros IIxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268211540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442682115423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442682115.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK